      "content": "that makes sense for the economic side. but for the debate, i really need to go deeper into the social logic people used back then. some people argue that these types of separations were actually a way to protect 'cultural cohesion'—basically saying that keeping different groups in specific areas helped preserve their distinct traditions and community ties without friction. could you expand on that? like, what would be the strongest academic-sounding argument for why segregation or strict residential separation was seen as a positive thing for maintaining social stability or cultural integrity?",
